{"id":"1608.08282","submitter":"Zachary Mesyan","authors":"Zachary Mesyan","title":"Infinite-Dimensional Triangularization","comments":"22 pages. The second version contains improvements to some of the\n  results and their proofs, as well as to the exposition. There is also a new\n  section on inverses","journal-ref":"Journal of Pure and Applied Algebra, Volume 222, (2018) 1529-1547","doi":"10.1016/j.jpaa.2017.07.010","report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The goal of this paper is to generalize the theory of triangularizing\nmatrices to linear transformations of an arbitrary vector space, without\nplacing any restrictions on the dimension of the space or on the base field. We\ndefine a transformation T of a vector space V to be \"triangularizable\" if V has\na well-ordered basis such that T sends each vector in that basis to the\nsubspace spanned by basis vectors no greater than it. We then show that the\nfollowing conditions (among others) are equivalent: (1) T is triangularizable,\n(2) every finite-dimensional subspace of V is annihilated by f(T) for some\npolynomial f that factors into linear terms, (3) there is a maximal\nwell-ordered set of subspaces of V that are invariant under T, (4) T can be put\ninto a crude version of the Jordan canonical form. We also show that any finite\ncollection of commuting triangularizable transformations is simultaneously\ntriangularizable, we describe the closure of the set of triangularizable\ntransformations in the standard topology on the algebra of all transformations\nof V , and we extend to transformations that satisfy a polynomial the classical\nfact that the double-centralizer of a matrix is the algebra generated by that\nmatrix.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Aug 2016 23:22:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2017 22:00:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-03-21"}
